main event: Sighting of a pinpoint, single white object of approximately second magnitude with no sound by crew of the USS G.K. Mackenzie in the Pacific Ocean.
interesting points: The object was sighted at an altitude of 23,530 feet, crossing the celestial sphere at an approximate heading of 110 degrees.
The object was observed for a duration of approximately 2 minutes, from 2700/10073Z to 1912/10073Z, and was lost from sight at an altitude of 4,000 feet due to clouds.
The observation was made by LT JG Antonino Rossman, USNR and LT JG Thomas Krakker, USN, who reported the reliability of the sighting as 'excellent'.
The weather conditions at the time of the sighting included partly cloudy skies, unlimited ceiling, 9 miles of visibility, and 3/10 cloud cover with shadows in the northeast quadrant.
The report concludes that the object was likely the Gemini 5 capsule on its 94th orbit.
result: The object was identified as the Gemini 5 capsule on its 94th orbit.
sighted object: a pinpoint, single white object of approximately second magnitude
witnesses: LT JG Antonino Rossman, USNR and LT JG Thomas Krakker, USN
